## Extending Egger's test: PET

:::: {.columns}

::: {.column width="50%"}
* Use Egger's regression line, but do not focus on slope, but on the ***intercept***!
* What is the expected ES at maximum precision (i.e., zero SE)?
* Intercept = estimate for true underlying effect correct for small-study effects
* PET = precision effect test
:::

::: {.column width="50%"}
![](img/eggers_regression_test_2.png){style="margin-top: -1.5em;"}
:::

::::

:::: aside
::: {.smaller}
Stanley, T. D., & Doucouliagos, H. (2013). Meta-regression approximations to reduce publication selection bias. Research Synthesis Methods, 5(1), 60–78. 
<http://doi.org/10.1002/jrsm.1095>
:::
::::

## PET-PEESE
### (Stanley & Doucou)

::: {.smallest}
* PEESE = precision-effect estimate with standard error ➙ effect size is regressed on the variance rather than standard error
* As in PET: Intercept is interpreted as estimate of true effect
* Simulation studies show: PET underestimates if true effect is non-zero, PEESE overestimates if true effect is zero.
* ➙ Suggestion: If PET intercept is not significant with p > .05, (i.e.: corrected ES does not differ from zero), use the PET intercept as estimate. If PET intercept significantly differs from zero, use PEESE intercept as estimate.
* No real theoretical foundation - just the ad-hoc solution that worked best.
:::


::: {.cell}

```{.r .cell-code}
# R Code
PET = lm(d~se, weights = 1/v)
PEESE = lm(d~se^2, weights = 1/v)
```
:::


