## Informed skepticism
### (“detection of Don’ts”)

* We have indicators which allow to evaluate the credibility and evidential value of a line of research
* ***p***-curve, R-index/ excess significance, TIVA, meta-regression techniques
* None of these techniques is perfect - but look out for (converging) **red flags** 
* Use these flags for informed skepticism (not for a "witch hunt" or "replication police")

## Red flags

::: {style="margin-top: -40px;"}
![](img/flag_red.png){height="100px"}
:::

::: {style="margin-top: -20px;"}
* Sweeping claims, counterintuitive, and shocking results
* Most ***p*** values are in the range of .03 – .05
  * ***p***-curve is not right-skewed
  * TIVA: Smaller variance of ***p***-values than expected
* A highly cited result, but no direct replications have been published so far
* Too good to be true
  * R-index < 40% / “Excess significance”
  * Biased meta-analysis: Asymmetric funnel plot
:::

:::: aside
::: {.smaller}
<http://www.nicebread.de/in-the-era-of-repligate-what-are-valid-cues-for-the-trustworthiness-of-a-study/>
